@node Objective
@chapter Objective
@cindex objective

The @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package is intended to provide compatibility with @cite{UNIX System
V Release 4} networking components based on the Transport Provider Interface and the XTI/TLI
interface described in X/Open Networking Services, in a single add-on package to @cite{Linux
Fast-STREAMS}.  One purpose in achieving this compatibility is the porting of legacy applications
from @cite{UNIX} to @cite{Linux} using the capabilities of @dfn{STREAMS} and @cite{Linux
Fast-STREAMS}.

Both the Transport Provider Interface and the XTI/TLI library APIs are designed to be transport
provider neutral.  Both the service primitive interface and function call interface are designed to
be transport provider independent to as large a degree as possible.  Therefore, this
@cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package does not provide any transport providers of its own.  It merely
provides the Transport Provider Interface and the XTI/TLI library interface and applies them in a
transport independent fashion to a wide range of specific transport protocols.

For transport providers based on the Internet Protocol suite, the
@file{strinet-@value{VERSION_STRINET}} package, @manref{strinet(5)}, provides TPI and XTI/TLI
compatible transport providers; the @file{strsctp-@value{VERSION_STRSCTP}} package,
@manref{strsctp(5)}, provides a TPI and XTI compatible implementation of the Stream Control
Transmission Protocol (SCTP) for @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS}.  The
@file{striso-@value{VERSION_STRISO}} package, @manref{striso(5)}, provides TPI and XTI compliant
transport providers for OSI/ISO protocols.

At the time that the @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} was being developed there existed an XTI
implementation written by Ole Husgaard, but the tirdwr and timod modules were deeply flawed and the
library itself was not thread-safe and did not support all functions and capabilities of XTI.
Therefore, the @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} @dfn{STREAMS} modules and library were written from the
start to be thread-safe and fully compliant with the XTI/TLI specifications in XNS
5.2.@footnote{@cite{The Open Group} making the specifications available for individual download
helped.}

The result is a stable, production grade, 64-bit clean XTI/TLI library implementation for
@cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS}.

